  "opinion": "As a fitness trainer in Washington DC with a vocational diploma and a background where one parent holds a PhD, I’ve seen firsthand how stereotypes can shape people’s confidence in their abilities. Stereotype threat in STEM isn’t just an academic concept—it’s the quiet anxiety that students from underrepresented groups feel when they’re reminded they’re part of a group historically marginalized in science, technology, engineering, and math fields. For example, when a student from a low-income background or a minority group hears a teacher say, 'You’re not really cut out for this,' it can trigger a stress response that hinders their performance, even if they’re capable. I’ve worked with clients who’ve struggled with math because they internalized the idea that they weren’t 'math people.' This isn’t about innate ability—it’s about the psychological burden of being labeled. Addressing stereotype threat is crucial. In my work, I focus on building self-efficacy through positive reinforcement and creating safe spaces where everyone feels valued. Schools should implement mentorship programs that pair students with role models who look like them in STEM careers, and educators should avoid language that reinforces stereotypes. It’s not just about fixing the system—it’s about empowering individuals to believe in themselves. As someone who grew up in a household where one parent was a scientist, I know that when kids see someone like them succeeding, it changes everything. The solution isn’t a quick fix but a cultural shift that starts with acknowledging these challenges and giving people the tools to overcome them.",
